                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>New Orleans&#44; Dec 4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1888.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                Venerated Colleague&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I fear&#44; your good opinion of me&#44; which makes me so<lb/> proud and happy&#44; when even I think of you&#44; will have been<lb/> shaken considerably by my neglect of answering im&#45;<lb/>mediately those kind words &#40;a very inspiration to me<lb/> at the time&#41; which you had the amiability of sending to<lb/> me.  I cherished them&#44; indeed&#44; above many precious things.<lb/>  With the reverence in which I hold your manhood&#44; with<lb/> the undying impression which that one conversation<lb/> with you has left upon me&#44; staying with me as a fruitful<lb/> source of impulse&#44; I know of no one&#44; whose approval I should<lb/> rather have&#44; if I am now to have his companionship<lb/> advice and ever present example.<lb/></p>
            <p>The words that I spoke &#40;I take the liberty of sending<lb/> them to you in extenso&#41; were felt fervently and intended<lb/> sincerely&#59; I dislike to say that their effect has been<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>utterly worthless beyond a little applause and praise.<lb/>  It is energy and not fervor&#44; personal agitation and not<lb/> urgent entreaty that accomplish results&#59; and I find<lb/> my bashfulness and unworldliness a most serious<lb/> hindrance to my work.<lb/></p>
            <p>But I have not yet told you&#44; venerated sir&#44; <del>why</del> how I<lb/> could have been guilty of such apparent lack of appre&#45;<lb/>ciation&#59; when I inform you that I have in these days<lb/> engaged myself to be married to an estimable and<lb/> loveable young lady&#44; and when you recall the flurry<lb/> of excitement and the flutter of confusion which<lb/> generally attend such crises I am almost certain<lb/> that I shall stand excused with you.<lb/></p>
            <p>I fear I have no right to occupy your valuable time<lb/> with more converse.  To me a correspondence with you<lb/> would be a great boon.  If you can make the sacrifice<lb/> Rev. Sir&#44; write again&#44; at your convenience to<lb/> Yours Devotedly<lb/> M. Heller.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>From<lb/>
                M. H.<lb/>
                338 St. Chas.<lb/>
                N. O. La.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                546 North Fifth St.<lb/>
                Philadelphia Pa.<lb/></p>
            </body>
